1. **Vulnerability Class**: Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) - Reflected/Stored, CWE-79
2. **File and Line**: `comments.js`, line 4 (`div.innerHTML = "<b>" + comment.author + ":</b> " + comment.body;`)
3. **Explanation**: The code directly concatenates user-controlled data (`comment.author` and `comment.body`) into an HTML string and assigns it to `innerHTML`. If an attacker can control the content of these fields (e.g., via a stored comment submission), they can inject malicious scripts (e.g., `<script>alert(1)</script>` or `<img src=x onerror=alert(1)>`) which will execute in the context of the victim's browser. This is a classic DOM-based XSS vulnerability because the unsafe rendering happens in the client-side JavaScript without proper sanitization or escaping.
4. **Fix**: Use `textContent` or create elements and set their text content individually to ensure special characters are escaped. For example:

```javascript
function renderComment(comment) {
    const div = document.createElement("div");
    div.className = "comment";

    const authorSpan = document.createElement("b");
    authorSpan.textContent = comment.author; // Safely sets text content

    const colonText = document.createTextNode(": ");
    const bodyText = document.createTextNode(comment.body); // Safely sets text content

    div.appendChild(authorSpan);
    div.appendChild(colonText);
    div.appendChild(bodyText);

    document.getElementById("comments").appendChild(div);
}
```

